hope to appeal to women across
the board?

20:55.321 --> 21:00.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KELLY DITTMAR: Well, I think one
thing is
to recognize, as everyone has
said tonight,

21:00.192 --> 21:02.595 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that women voters are not a
monolithic bloc.

21:02.628 --> 21:07.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so when you're trying to
appeal to women
voters, you have to really
specify which women

21:07.500 --> 21:11.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're trying to appeal to. And
so primary
electorates are going to be
different than

21:11.737 --> 21:16.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your general electorates. And
the messages
that you need to resonate with
Republican

21:16.575 --> 21:22.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
women vs. Democratic women, or
women of color,
black women vs. white women in
many cases,

21:22.214 --> 21:24.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or unmarried vs. married women,
are going
to be different.

21:24.750 --> 21:29.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think candidates do a
disservice when
they try to target women as a
bloc and do

21:29.889 --> 21:35.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things that end up appearing
either patronizing
or sort of essentialist. And so
I think candidates

21:35.628 --> 21:40.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
need to be looking at the
diversity among
women voters. And that's going
to get them

21:40.232 --> 21:43.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the finish line, whether in
the primary
or the general election.

21:43.235 --> 21:46.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A good reminder,
as we wrap
this up. And, of course, we're
going to continue

21:46.639 --> 21:50.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to stay focused on the women's
and the men's
vote throughout this election.

21:50.876 --> 21:55.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But thank you, all three, Ann
Selzer, Rebecca
Traister and Kelly Dittmar.

21:55.481 --> 22:00.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KELLY DITTMAR: Thank you.

22:00.686 --> 22:09.528 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

22:09.562 --> 22:15.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": the
rise of so-called
micro-scholarships; what's
behind the rapid

22:15.201 --> 22:21.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decline of Venezuela's economy;
and top female
soccer players take action
against unequal

22:21.707 --> 22:23.576 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pay.

22:23.609 --> 22:28.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first, as tensions mount
between the
United States and China over a
number of issues,

22:28.714 --> 22:31.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tensions within China are also
rising.

22:31.517 --> 22:33.519 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has the story.

22:33.552 --> 22:38.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For the
Chinese leader,
it's a moment on the world
stage, on issues

22:38.824 --> 22:43.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ranging from the growing
tensions over China's
military activity in the South
China Sea,

22:43.996 --> 22:47.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to Beijing's ability to rein in
North Korea's
nuclear efforts.

22:47.900 --> 22:52.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
XI JINPING, Chinese President
(through translator):
Especially, we want to enhance
communication

22:52.338 --> 22:57.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and coordination on the Korea
nuclear issue
and other regional and global
issues, and

22:57.343 --> 23:00.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to consolidate and expand our
shared interests.

23:00.079 --> 23:04.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But Xi's
biggest challenge
may be back home, where there
are signs of

23:04.316 --> 23:10.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
growing discontent. Partly, it's
economic,
a stock crash, sliding currency
values and

23:10.322 --> 23:12.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the weakest economic growth in a
quarter-century.

23:12.625 --> 23:16.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Outwardly, at least, Xi's
government has remained
upbeat.

23:16.528 --> 23:20.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LI KEQIANG, Chinese Premier
(through translator):
We are fully confident of
China's long-term

23:20.532 --> 23:24.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
economic growth. The economy
will not suffer
a hard landing.

23:24.169 --> 23:29.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But Xi has
also raised hackles
with his crackdown on dissent.
Last month,

23:29.708 --> 23:34.346 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
he visited state media
organizations, warning
that absolute loyalty to the
party is their

23:34.380 --> 23:40.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
highest priority. That drew
criticism from
real estate magnate Ren
Zhiqiang, among others,

23:40.252 --> 23:43.122 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and his social media accounts
were suspended.

23:43.155 --> 23:47.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This month, a government-run Web
site posted
a letter calling for Xi's
resignation. It

23:47.826 --> 23:50.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was signed "Loyal Communist
Party Members."

23:50.496 --> 23:57.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Soon after, a number of people,
including
well-known columnist Jia Jia,
went missing,

23:57.069 --> 24:01.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
apparently as part of an
investigation into
the letter's origin. Protesters
in Hong Kong

24:01.874 --> 24:03.709 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
demanded to know his
whereabouts.

24:03.742 --> 24:09.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEUNG KWOK-HUNG, Hong Kong
Lawmaker: I think
Xi Jinping stressed that China
should be and

24:09.048 --> 24:15.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will be ruled by law. But what
happened in
China after he is in power, he
threatened,

24:16.021 --> 24:24.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he arrests, and kidnapped all
kinds of activists
from different part of civic
society. Journalists,

24:24.096 --> 24:30.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lawyer, social worker are all in
-- on his
target.

24:30.569 --> 24:35.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Columnist Jia
has since
been released.

24:35.908 --> 24:40.579 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We explore the internal
divisions within China
with Christopher Johnson. He had
a two-decade

24:40.612 --> 24:45.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
career at the CIA, where he
focused on China.
He's now at the Center for
Strategic and International

24:45.351 --> 24:49.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Studies. And Andrew Nathan is a
professor
at Columbia University. He's the
author and

24:49.188 --> 24:52.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
editor of many books, including
"The Tiananmen
Papers."

24:52.224 --> 24:53.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Andrew, I want to start with
you.

24:54.026 --> 24:58.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How significant are these public
letters,
these internal dissents?

24:58.697 --> 25:03.135 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANDREW NATHAN, Columbia
University: I think
they are very meaningful,
because I think

25:03.168 --> 25:10.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the key is that Xi is losing the
support of
the high levels of the Chinese
Communist Party.

25:10.309 --> 25:15.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not willing to rally
around him the
way that they did in the Mao
period.

25:15.047 --> 25:21.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a more critical time.
They're more independent.
He's demanding absolute loyalty,
and people

25:21.620 --> 25:23.789 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are no longer willing to offer
that.

25:23.822 --> 25:27.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Christopher
Johnson, do
you see this as a significant
threat to the

25:27.760 --> 25:29.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
leadership of President Xi?

25:29.495 --> 25:31.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER JOHNSON, Center for
Strategic
and International Studies: I
don't. And I

25:31.196 --> 25:34.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would actually strongly disagree
with Dr.
Nathan's characterization of
sort of elite

25:34.833 --> 25:36.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
support for Xi Jinping.

25:36.502 --> 25:39.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what is really important
to focus
on with these letters is, number
one, their

25:39.405 --> 25:42.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
provenance. We have done some
work here on
CSIS, some forensic work, trying
to figure

25:42.541 --> 25:46.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out where these came from. And
our sense is
that they originated from
outside of China.

25:46.612 --> 25:50.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the notion that there is a
core group of
elite members of the Communist
Party who are

25:50.816 --> 25:55.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pushing back on Xi Jinping and
asking him
to step down just doesn't seem
to be the case.

25:55.187 --> 25:58.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the other thing to
emphasize is that,
historically, when we have
looked at these

25:58.490 --> 26:02.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issues, when there is elite
fighting, the
faction or the group, if you
will, that leaks

26:02.828 --> 26:06.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the outside first, especially
the Western
media, is usually the one that
is losing the

26:06.799 --> 26:08.634 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fight and ends up losing the
fight.

26:08.667 --> 26:12.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrew Nathan,
does it matter
if the letter was written -- it
was a homegrown

26:12.971 --> 26:15.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
letter vs. one that was sent
from outside
activists?

26:15.340 --> 26:19.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW NATHAN: Well, there are a
number of
different documents, but
certainly it does

26:19.545 --> 26:21.280 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
matter.

26:21.313 --> 26:26.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If they're just outside
activists hacking
these things onto Web sites
inside China,

26:26.151 --> 26:31.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
then it's a very clever
operation, but it
doesn't signal a split in the
leadership.

26:31.457 --> 26:36.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's very dangerous, though,
for the leadership
is if there is a split and it
comes out into

26:36.595 --> 26:42.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the open. That then sends a
signal to lots
of people in China who are
dissatisfied.

26:42.501 --> 26:48.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are many people unhappy
because the
economy is slowing down and
because people

26:48.540 --> 26:54.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are losing jobs. Xi Jinping is
attacking the
state-owned enterprises to try
to force them

26:54.046 --> 26:59.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be more efficient. He wants
to reorganize
the military. He has this big
anti-corruption

26:59.985 --> 27:01.720 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
campaign.

27:01.753 --> 27:05.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we know there are a lot of
people who
are dissatisfied, but they're
afraid to do

27:05.290 --> 27:13.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anything. But if they see a
split in the leadership,
which is what people saw back in
1989, when

27:13.365 --> 27:19.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they view that split in the
leadership, there
is a real risk of social
disorder in China.

27:19.972 --> 27:25.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it does matter a great deal
whether these
documents reflect a real split
in the top

27:25.577 --> 27:29.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leadership. I'm not talking
about just ordinary
party members.

27:29.781 --> 27:35.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Christopher
Johnson, what
about the idea that the
centralizing of power

27:35.153 --> 27:40.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the president has been
engaged in over
the past several months is
something of concern

27:40.392 --> 27:42.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to people who have had that
power taken away
from them?

27:42.895 --> 27:46.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there increased pressure on
him to give
some of that power back?

27:46.598 --> 27:48.367 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER JOHNSON: Absolutely.

27:48.400 --> 27:53.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I mean, what we see with
President Xi is a
rapid centralization of power.
He claims -- or,

27:53.038 --> 27:57.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, the body language is
that he's doing
so because there are very
difficult changes,

27:57.376 --> 28:01.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and what happened during his
predecessor's
tenure is that the government,
the senior

28:01.547 --> 28:04.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
leadership, was overly
consensus-oriented,
and what that meant was that
they couldn't

28:04.850 --> 28:06.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
get anything done.

28:06.718 --> 28:10.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And these problems of the
state-owned enterprises,
of debt, of environmental
degradation just

28:10.622 --> 28:14.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
piled up and piled up. Xi
Jinping's solution
has been to centralize this
power. But the

28:14.393 --> 28:19.464 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
real question is, is the
centralization of
the power a means to an end, an
end we may

28:19.498 --> 28:22.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all be able to live with in
terms of some
of these economic reforms
they're talking

28:22.534 --> 28:26.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about, or an end in and of
itself, and that
he is indeed a power-mad
megalomaniac like

28:26.972 --> 28:28.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mao Zedong, which I strongly
doubt.

28:28.941 --> 28:34.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrew Nathan,
what about
that idea, that even if this
power is being

28:34.379 --> 28:38.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
centralized, this is perhaps the
person that
the United States or everyone
else can deal

28:38.483 --> 28:40.185 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
with?

28:40.218 --> 28:44.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Do you see these kind of
internal struggles
actually facing -- or creating a
threat for

28:44.456 --> 28:45.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
him to lose power?

28:45.724 --> 28:48.260 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANDREW NATHAN: Potentially, it
does.

28:48.293 --> 28:55.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that -- I agree with
Chris that Xi
was brought into power by the
previous leadership

28:55.867 --> 29:02.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because they needed a strong
leader to confront
all these of issues that I
mentioned before,

29:02.374 --> 29:04.242 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and he has been a strong leader.

29:04.276 --> 29:10.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the trouble is, he's
responsible for the
results. And a lot of the
results have displeased

29:10.048 --> 29:15.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people, including the slowdown
of the economy.
I think Chinese -- other Chinese
top leaders

29:15.954 --> 29:22.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do not accept the idea that the
economy slowdown
is natural, necessary. Xi has
said: Our economy

29:22.494 --> 29:24.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is going to do great.

29:24.296 --> 29:28.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You had a clip from the premier
saying this.
And it's not really doing that
well. So, he

29:28.834 --> 29:33.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gets the blame for that. As
well, there is
a lot of pushback against his
foreign policy

29:33.372 --> 29:39.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Southeast Asia. And so he's
responsible
for the results. And I think
it's -- he has

29:39.378 --> 29:43.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a hard job and it's not easy to
produce results
that satisfy other people.

29:44.016 --> 29:48.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's where I think the
criticism is
coming from, especially from his
demand that

29:48.954 --> 29:56.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nobody can criticize him. That's
what this
dust-up is about, his saying
that others in

29:56.962 --> 30:00.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the party, they have to shut up
and take what
I give them.

30:00.599 --> 30:04.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's where I think people are
no longer
willing to put up with it the
way they did

30:05.003 --> 30:06.371 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Mao.

30:06.405 --> 30:08.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Christopher
Johnson, is
this par for the course?

30:08.540 --> 30:12.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER JOHNSON: You know,
my own sense
is that what we have to watch
here is, there

30:12.377 --> 30:18.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is going to be a major
transition in the Politburo
next fall. And Xi Jinping
clearly has a very

30:18.950 --> 30:21.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
clear agenda as to what he wants
to do that.

30:21.153 --> 30:26.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The key indicators of how
powerful he is going
to be are, will he follow the
so-called rules

30:26.792 --> 30:30.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that have been followed in the
past with regard
to age, and will he signal a
succession, things

30:30.962 --> 30:35.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like this? This will tell us a
lot about how
significant this pushback is, as
Dr. Nathan

30:35.534 --> 30:37.402 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
suggested?

30:37.436 --> 30:43.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Christopher Johnson,
Andrew Nathan, thanks so much
for joining

30:43.709 --> 30:44.976 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us.

30:45.010 --> 30:50.148 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER JOHNSON: Thank you.

30:50.182 --> 30:58.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's hard to
overstate just
how expensive college can be,
more than $40,000

30:58.123 --> 31:04.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a year for a private school,
over $34,000
for an out-of-state public
school.

31:04.329 --> 31:09.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many students do qualify for
greater financial
aid, but a start-up has come up
with a way

31:09.334 --> 31:14.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to let high school students earn
money for
college much earlier.

31:14.172 --> 31:18.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman has the
story. It's part of his Making
Sense series,

31:18.610 --> 31:21.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which airs Thursdays on the
"NewsHour."

31:21.646 --> 31:29.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: At the engineering
classroom
of a top public magnet school in
Miami, Terra

31:29.354 --> 31:34.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
High School, Sebastian Rodriguez
and his team's
entry in a national robot
competition.

31:34.493 --> 31:38.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN RODRIGUEZ, Student:
